title: User query: Plan description from client LLM
log: Find the top 100 customers who have placed large-volume orders, where a large order is defined as an order whose total quantity exceeds 300. For each qualifying order, return the customer name, customer key, order key, order date, total price, and the total quantity of the order. Sort by total price desc. Output the results to a textfile.SQL_QUERY:

title: Agent: SpecifierAgent Output
log: Identify the top 100 customers who have placed large-volume orders (where a large order is defined as an order with total quantity greater than 300). For every qualifying order belonging to these customers, return the following fields: customer name, customer key, order key, order date, total price, and total quantity of the order. Sort the results by total price in descending order. Output the results to a text file. SQL_QUERY:

log.thoughts: Selected the core relational sources typically containing customer, order, and line item quantities to compute per-order totals and filter for large orders (>300).

steps.detailed_description: Load the customers table and the orders table with all their relevant columns required for the analysis (customer_key, customer_name, order_key, order_date, total_price, total_quantity, and any keys used for joins).
Filter orders to keep only those with total_quantity > 300 (large orders). Input: orders table. Output: large_orders dataset containing orders that qualify as large.
Join the large_orders dataset with the customers table on customer_key to attach customer_name and retain customer_key for downstream selection. Output: large_orders_with_customer.

Identify the top 100 customers by the sum of total_price across their large orders, then filter large_orders_with_customer to include only rows whose customer_key is in this top-100 set. Sort the resulting records by total_price in descending order. Output: final_qualified_orders_with_customer, containing customer_name, customer_key, order_key, order_date, total_price, and total_quantity, already ordered by total_price descending.
Write the final results to a text file as specified (textual output file containing the selected fields).

log.thoughts: We load both customers and orders, filter for large orders, join to attach customer details, identify the top-100 customers by spend on large orders, filter to those customers, sort by total_price, and finally output the selected fields to a text file. This keeps the plan to 5 steps and maintains clear data lineage.

log.thoughts: Refined plan now joins customers with their orders, filters large-volume orders (>300), projects the required fields, sorts by total_price descending, and outputs to a text file. This aligns with the request to identify top customers by large orders and report corresponding order details. Note: top-100 constraint is not explicitly enforceable with available operators here; the plan produces all qualifying records sorted by price, which can be further limited downstream if needed.
